  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json">{JSON.stringify({
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is keratoconus?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Keratoconus is a progressive eye condition in which the cornea thins and takes on a cone shape instead of a normal dome shape. This distorts vision and makes it difficult to correct with standard glasses or soft contact lenses. It is diagnosed with corneal topography."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How is keratoconus diagnosed?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Keratoconus is diagnosed primarily with corneal topography, a painless test that maps the exact shape of the cornea. Topography can detect keratoconus in early stages before significant symptoms appear. Ópticas Jarmar in Tijuana has corneal topography equipment on-site."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can keratoconus be treated?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "There is no definitive cure, but two complementary strategies exist: slowing progression with corneal cross-linking (CXL), and improving vision with scleral lenses, rigid gas-permeable lenses, or in advanced cases, corneal transplant. Cross-linking stops progression but does not reverse existing damage."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Do scleral lenses work for keratoconus?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. Scleral lenses are the most effective option for improving vision in moderate and advanced keratoconus. By vaulting over the irregular cornea and creating a fluid reservoir, they neutralize the visual distortions caused by the cone and achieve visual acuities that conventional lenses cannot reach."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Where can I get keratoconus diagnosed and treated in Tijuana?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Ópticas Jarmar in Zona Urbana Río, Tijuana has corneal topography and over 10 years of experience in visual rehabilitation for keratoconus using scleral lenses. Director Optometrist Jorge Aranda Tello specializes in these cases. WhatsApp: +52 664 579 1970. English spoken."
          }
        }
      ]
    })}</script>
